## Responsive Design

Use custom breakpoint syntax for consistent responsive design:

```tsx
// ❌ Don't use default Tailwind breakpoints
<div className="w-full sm:w-1/2 md:w-1/3 lg:w-1/4">
  {/* content */}
</div>

// ✅ Use custom breakpoint syntax
<div className="w-full @xl:w-1/2 @3xl:w-1/3 @5xl:w-1/4">
  {/* content */}
</div>

// ❌ Don't use default max-width breakpoints
<div className="block max-sm:hidden max-md:flex-col max-lg:gap-2">
  {/* content */}
</div>

// ✅ Use custom max-width breakpoint syntax
<div className="block @max-xl:hidden @max-3xl:flex-col @max-5xl:gap-2">
  {/* content */}
</div>
```

### Breakpoint Reference

```css
/* Min-width breakpoints */
@xl: 640px    /* replaces sm: */
@3xl: 1024px  /* replaces md: */
@5xl: 1280px  /* replaces lg: */

/* Max-width breakpoints */
@max-xl: 639px    /* replaces max-sm: */
@max-3xl: 1023px  /* replaces max-md: */
@max-5xl: 1279px; /* replaces max-lg: */
```

## Examples

<example>
```tsx
function MyComponent({ 
  title, 
  description, 
  isActive = false 
}: { 
  title: string; 
  description?: string; 
  isActive?: boolean 
}) {
  return (
    <div className="bg-background text-foreground p-4 rounded-[var(--radius)]">
      <h2 className="text-primary font-bold">{title}</h2>
      {description && <p className="text-muted-foreground">{description}</p>}
      {isActive && <Badge variant="outline">Active</Badge>}
    </div>
  );
}
```
This pattern uses destructured props with inline TypeScript types, making the component cleaner and more readable. It also uses CSS variables from globals.css and UI components from the component library.
</example>

<example type="invalid">
